---
import Layout from '../../../components/layout/Layout.astro';
import ArtworkSchema from '../../../components/seo/ArtworkSchema.astro';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const title = 'In Memoriam';

const img1 = (await import('../../../assets/images/obras/in-memoriam/in-memoriam-01.jpg')).default;
const img2 = (await import('../../../assets/images/obras/in-memoriam/port-003.jpg')).default;
const img3 = (await import('../../../assets/images/obras/in-memoriam/port-004.jpg')).default;
const img4 = (await import('../../../assets/images/obras/in-memoriam/port-005.jpg')).default;
---

<Layout
  lang={lang}
  title="In Memoriam — Work"
  description="In Memoriam (2001). Ephemeral sculpture — ice, glass, water. 300 kg, 20 hours. Alianza Colombo Francesa, Bogota. Maria Elvira Escallon."
>


  <ArtworkSchema
    title="In Memoriam"
    year="2001"
    medium="Ephemeral sculpture, ice"
    description="Ice sculpture that gradually melted at the Alianza Colombo Francesa, Bogota."
    url="https://mariaelviraescallon.com/en/works/in-memoriam/"
  />

  <article class="work-page">
    <div class="container">

      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="work-page__header">
        <p class="label">Work / 003</p>
        <h1>{title}</h1>
        <p class="work-page__meta">2001 &nbsp;/&nbsp; Ephemeral sculpture — ice, glass, water &nbsp;/&nbsp; 300 kg, duration 20 hours &nbsp;/&nbsp; Alianza Colombo Francesa, Bogota</p>
      </header>

      <!-- Main gallery -->
      <div class="work-page__gallery">
        <img src={img1.src} alt="In Memoriam — Doric ice column dissolving in water urn, 2001" loading="eager">
        <img src={img2.src} alt="In Memoriam — Intermediate state of the ice column dissolution" loading="lazy">
        <img src={img3.src} alt="In Memoriam — Detail of the transformation process of ice into water" loading="lazy">
        <img src={img4.src} alt="In Memoriam — Glass container with water at the end of the process" loading="lazy">
      </div>

      <!-- Text + Technical sheet -->
      <div class="work-page__body">
        <div class="work-page__text">

          <p class="curatorial">
            A 300-kilogram ice column dissolving slowly in water over twenty hours inside
            a glass container. The work captures the passage of time as irreversible material
            loss, making duration visible as a sculptural phenomenon. The viewer witnesses
            the transformation — from solid monument to liquid absence. Nothing remains.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            The process of dissolution is the work itself. There is no privileged moment of
            contemplation: each instant is equally valid and simultaneously ephemeral.
            The ice column functions as a clock that measures its own disappearance,
            a monument that consumes itself in the very act of existing.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            The glass container operates as both display case and receptacle — it exhibits the
            sculpture while collecting its remains. At the end of the twenty hours, what
            was once a monumental column is only water: the form has disappeared completely,
            but the matter remains transformed. The transparency of the glass makes
            every stage of this metamorphosis visible.
          </p>

          <h3 style="margin-top: var(--s4);">CONTEXT</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            This ephemeral sculpture embodies Escallon's interest in temporal processes
            and the vulnerability of materials. The ice column functions as both monument
            and anti-monument — its grandeur resides precisely in its impermanence.
          </p>
          <p style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            <em>In Memoriam</em> belongs to a tradition of process-based sculpture that
            includes Joseph Beuys's interventions with fat and felt as well as Andy
            Goldsworthy's ice sculptures. However, Escallon's work distinguishes itself
            through its specific symbolic charge: in the Colombian context of 2001,
            the dissolution of a monument acquires inevitable political and social
            resonances — the fragility of institutions, the loss of collective memory,
            the impermanence of everything that has been built.
          </p>
          <p style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            The work anticipates Escallon's central concern with temporality as
            sculptural material, a theme she would develop with greater complexity in
            <em>Nuevas Floras</em> (where time transforms the intervention over the
            course of years) and in <em>En estado de coma</em> (where she documents the
            slow dissolution of a heritage building).
          </p>
        </div>

        <aside class="work-page__ficha">
          <h4>TECHNICAL SHEET</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            <strong>In Memoriam</strong><br>
            2001<br><br>
            Ephemeral sculpture.<br>
            Ice, glass, water.<br><br>
            Weight: 300 kg<br>
            Duration: 20 hours<br><br>
            Alianza Colombo Francesa, Bogota.
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">EXHIBITIONS</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            Alianza Colombo Francesa, Bogota, 2001
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">TEXTS</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            <a href="/maria-elvira-escallon/en/texts/" style="color: var(--moss); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--paper-dark);">
              Related texts
            </a>
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">HOW TO CITE</h4>
          <div class="ficha" style="font-size: 0.65rem;">
            Escallon, M.E. (2001). <em>In Memoriam</em>.
            Ephemeral sculpture. Available at:
            mariaelviraescallon.com/en/works/in-memoriam/
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>

</Layout>

<style>
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    }
</style>
